Selexipag in Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension: Most updated evidence
from recent preclinical and clinical studies
Abstract
Pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) is a relatively rare disease which due to
its chronic nature has always been difficult to treat effectively. Selexipag is an
oral prostacyclin (PGI2) agonist, which was approved by US Food and Drug
Administration (US FDA) in December 2015 for the treatment of PAH. After its
success in Phase 1 and Phase 2 clinical trials regarding the convenient oral
twice daily dosing and low side-effect profile, selexipag raised the hope of
controlling the disease progression in PAH patients. In the recently completed
multi-centered Phase 3 study (GRIPHON), selexipag has been shown to reduce
the death and hospitalization due to PAH significantly, the effect being
consistent across different ranges of maintenance dose. In the same study,
selexipag use was also associated with an increase in 6-minute walk distance (a
measure of symptom severity) from baseline, but no significant improvement in
all-cause mortality could be observed. The results of the ongoing phase 3
studies (TRITON and TRANSIT-1) are expected to throw some more light on
its safety and efficacy of this novel molecule across various treatment scenarios.
Hence, our article aims to summarize all the available information from
preclinical and clinical studies published till date on the pharmacodynamics,
pharmacokinetics, efficacy, safety (in general and in scenarios like hepatic and
renal function impairment), significant drug interactions (with warfarin and
antiretroviral drugs), and clinical significance of oral selexipag in patients with
PAH.
KeyWords: GRIPHON; TRITON; TRANSIT-1; ACT-333679; Selexipag and
warfarin; Selexipag in hepatic impairment; Selexipag in renal dysfunction;
Selexipag on QT interval.
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
Introduction
Pulmonary hypertension (PH) is described by an increase in mean pulmonary
artery pressure (mPAP) up to 25 mmHg or greater at rest. [1] PH could be
because of primary elevation of pulmonary arterial pressure (pulmonary arterial
hypertension) or secondary to elevations of pulmonary venous or capillary
pressure (pulmonary venous hypertension).[2] WHO has classified PH into five
groups based on underlying mechanisms and etiologies. Group I PH, also
known as pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) has distinct pathogenesis from
other four groups.[3] The diagnostic criteria for PAH states that the pulmonary
arterial wedge pressure (PAWP), left ventricular end-diastolic pressure
(LVEDP) or left atrial pressure should be 15 mmHg or less, and the calculated
pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) must be three wood units, or greater.[4]
The commonest type of PAH is idiopathic PAH (IPAH), a sporadic disease with
no family history or associated risk factors. The other prominent causes of PAH
include genetic mutations, drugs, toxins, portal hypertension, connective tissue
diseases and HIV.[3] An invasive hemodynamic assessment by right heart
catheterization (RHC) is critical in diagnosis and evaluation of patients
suspected of having PAH.
Epidemiology of PAH
The estimated annual incidence of idiopathic PAH (IPAH) is around 1-3 cases
per million, which makes it a rare disease. [5] Results from a more recent
French registry showed the incidence rate of IPAH as 5.9/ million.[6] In a US-
based registry enrolling patients between 1982 and 2006, IPAH was the
commonest among causes of class 1 PAH in 578 patients.[7] Untreated PAH is
a progressively fatal disease, leading to right heart failure and subsequently
death. Over the years, death and hospitalization due to PAH have increased
significantly. The age-standardized mortality rate for PAH was found to be 5.8
per 1,00,000 population, with maximum mortality observed among African
American, and in patients aged > 85 years. Both death and hospitalization rates
were higher in women compared to men.[8] IPAH has an estimated prevalence
of 30%-50% among all classes of PAH.[9] Heritable PAH is most commonly
(80%) due to a mutation in the gene for BMPR-2 (Bone Morphogenic Protein
Receptor type-2), which is a member of the TGF-beta superfamily and a
mediator involved in apoptosis pathway of some cells.[10] Other genetic
mutations commonly associated with PAH are ALK-1 (Activin-like receptor
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
kinase-1), endoglin, and SMAD 9.[11-13] Although their etiologies differ, the
patients with IPAH and heritable PAH have near identical clinical presentation,
and their histopathological features are similar as well.[9]
Pathophysiology of PAH
PAH is characterized by the vasoconstriction of pulmonary arteries, smooth
muscle and endothelial cell proliferation, and vascular remodeling. Three major
pathways contribute to its development, involving endothelin (ET), nitric oxide
(NO), and prostacyclin (PGI2).[14] Endothelin-1 (ET-1) acts as a critical
mediator in initiation and progression of PAH.[15] It binds to ET -a and ET-b
receptors on smooth muscle and endothelial cells, leading to their proliferation
along with vasoconstriction and activation of fibroblasts, all of which ultimately
culminates into pulmonary vascular remodeling.[16-18] Endothelium-derived
nitric oxide (NO) acts on the guanylate cyclase enzyme to increase the amount
of cyclic guanylate monophosphate (c-GMP), which facilitates vasodilation and
inhibits the proliferation of vascular smooth muscle cells.[19,20] In PAH, the
production of this NO is found to be impaired, thus hastening the progression of
vascular remodeling in these patients.[21] Prostacyclin (PGI2) pathway has also
got a critical role in the development of PAH. PGI2 is a potent vasodilator with
noticeable anti-proliferative, antithrombotic, and anti-inflammatory effects. It
has been shown that PAH was associated with a decreased expression of the
enzyme prostacyclin synthase and reduced levels of endogenous PGI2. [22]
PGI2, after its release from the endothelial cells, acts as a potent systemic as
well as pulmonary vasodilator. This pathway has a downstream effector in the
form of inositol phosphate (IP) which gets activated upon stimulation with
prostacyclin and leads to increased cyclic adenosine monophosphate (c-AMP)
levels to cause vasodilation and resist proliferation in the pulmonary circulatory
system. [23] The salient features of pulmonary artery hypertension are
summarized in Table 1.
Current therapeutic options and their limitations in PAH
Till date, there is no single best therapeutic agent for advanced therapy in
patients with PAH. The therapeutic strategy is guided by the WHO functional
class of patients, right ventricular function, hemodynamics, and vasoreactivity
test results. Before the initiation of advanced treatment, it is therefore always
recommended that the patients with group 1 PAH undergo a vasoreactivity test.
For patients whose vasoreactivity test are positive, a trial of calcium channel
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
blocker (CCB) therapy with a dihydropyridine or diltiazem needs to be tried
before the initiation of treatment with prostanoids, endothelin receptor
antagonists, phosphodiesterase five inhibitors (PDE-5i), or guanylate cyclase
stimulant.[3] Advanced therapeutic options for PAH include drugs acting on ET
pathway i.e. ET receptor antagonists like bosentan and ambrisentan, and PDE-5
inhibitors (increase available cGMP level, a downstream signaling molecule of
NO pathway) like sildenafil or tadalafil.[24]
Prostacyclin analogs in the treatment of PAH
The drugs, currently in use, that target the prostacyclin pathway are
epoprostenol, iloprost, treprostinil, and beraprost, which are recommended
mostly for patients with an advanced PAH (World Health Organization
functional class IIIIV).[25] Epoprostenol was the first synthetic derivative of
endogenous prostacyclin, which was approved for use in PAH by US Food and
Drug Administration (FDA) in 1995.[26] Although epoprostenol has been
shown to cause a decrease in mortality in PAH patients when used in
combination with other drugs, its short half-life turned out to be its main
disadvantage as an intravenous catheter is required for its continuous
delivery.[27,28] The necessity of longer-acting prostacyclin analogs which can
be administered through intravenous, inhalational, and oral routes was widely
felt, and treprostinil was believed to be the perfect answer to this problem.
Despite having a longer half-life through subcutaneous and intravenous routes
of administration, and potential to cause a reduction in morbidity and mortality
in PAH patients, treprostinil also faced a similar challenge of patients non-
compliance.[29-32] As oral treprostinil and beraprost monotherapy failed to live
up to their expectations and inhaled iloprost was pushed back as a second-line
agent or add-on therapy in sequential combination regimens, the formulation of
an oral PGI2 agonist became the need of the hour.[16,33-36] A recent
observational study of patients with IPAH found that only 13% patients had a
positive vasoreactivity test, and only 54% of those receiving CCB therapy
showed a functional improvement after one year. Older prostanoids are the
culprit of having a very short half-life as well as cumbersome drug
administration process (continuous intravenous/subcutaneous pump or frequent
inhalations) and severe adverse effects (e.g. hypotension, accelerated hypoxia,
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
etc.) as well. [38] So there was always a need for the development of a new
prostacyclin agonist that is safe, easy to administer, has minimal interactions
and is yet effective in treating PAH.
Newer drugs in PAH
Among newest drugs in the arsenal, imatinib (a tyrosine kinase inhibitor) acts
through platelet-derived growth factor (PDGF) pathway and has been shown to
be particularly useful in scleroderma-associated PAH. Macitentan is the new
superior next generation endothelin receptor agonist (ERA). [37, 38] Riociguat
has been demonstrated to stimulate intracellular guanylate cyclase, independent
of NO and thereby has been found to be useful in patients with PAH and
chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension (CTEPH). [39]
Selexipag
Selexipag, approved by US FDA in December 2015, has shown its effectiveness
in the treatment of PAH in various pre-clinical and clinical trials. The molecule,
a selective prostacyclin receptor (IP) agonist, was given orphan drug
designation during development. [40] Selexipag, being an oral and well
tolerated (minor adverse effects like flushing and hypotension) drug, is a much
convenient option for patients, compared to other parenteral or inhalational
prostacyclin analogs used in PAH. Both selexipag (Uptravi, produced by
Acetilon) and ACT-333679 (active metabolite of selexipag) are functionally
distinct from other drugs targeting the PGI2 pathway as both are known to be
highly selective for the IP receptor. [23, 41-43] Selexipag, after its rapid
absorption, is hydrolyzed in the liver by the enzyme carboxylesterase-1 to
produce the active metabolite ACT-333679. This metabolite has a 13-fold
higher affinity than selexipag itself, and a 130-fold higher affinity for the IP
receptor, as compared to other prostaglandin receptors. Both the compounds
demonstrated high binding affinity towards human albumin and -acid
glycoprotein. The plasma protein binding is more than 99% for both the
compounds, and there was no absolute saturation level of binding with clinically
relevant concentration range. [44] This selectivity for the IP receptors prevents
dose-related side-effects like nausea and vomiting that might result from
activation of the other prostanoid receptors. [45] The mean half-lives of
selexipag and ACT-333679 are 0.72.3 hours and 9.414.22 hours respectively.
The maximum tolerated dose for selexipag is 1600 g, although bioequivalence
can be achieved between 8 x 200 g and 1 x 1,600 g at the steady state. [46,
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
47] Elimination time of selexipag is 7.9 hours. [43] Selexipag is mainly
eliminated via the hepatobiliary route as measured by the low urinary
concentration of ACT-333679. [47] The highlights of selexipag pharmacology
are described in Table 2.
Preclinical data on Selexipag
Selexipag is a selective prostacyclin receptor (IP receptor) agonist. A pre-
clinical study looked at whether this receptor-selectivity has an effect on the
vasorelaxant efficacy of ACT-333679 (active metabolite of selexipag). [48] The
effects of selexipag on normal pulmonary artery as well as monocrotaline
(MCT)-PAH rat were compared to another prostacyclin analog, treprostinil.
Both selexipag and its active metabolite were shown to evoke full relaxation of
pulmonary artery of controls, MCT-PAH rats, and artery pretreated with
vasoconstrictors (endothelin-1 or phenylephrine). In contrast, treprostinil caused
weaker relaxation in the normal pulmonary artery and could not relax
pulmonary artery of MCT-PAH rats. It failed to show any effect on
vasoconstrictor-treated pulmonary artery too. Selexipag or ACT-333679 did not
cause any contraction of pulmonary artery sample at all, whereas treprostinil
was shown to cause dose-dependent contraction which is thought to be
mediated by its action on EP 3 receptor. This EP 3 receptor mRNA expression
is found to be increased in MCT-PH rats, which can potentially affect the
efficacy of treprostinil in PAH. The study proved that the vasorelaxant efficacy
of selexipag or its active metabolite remains unaffected by factors associated
with PAH.
In another preclinical study, the vasorelaxant property of different prostacyclin
(PGI2) agonists (treprostinil, iloprost, and selexipag metabolite ACT-333679)
was assessed in rat pulmonary artery and vein, pre-contracted with a
thromboxane mimetic (U46619).[49] It was found that the vasorelaxation
induced by treprostinil and iloprost were inhibited (completely or partially) with
the use of IP receptor antagonists (RO1138452 and RO3244794), whereas
RO1138452 failed to attenuate the relaxation due to ACT-333679 in both
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
pulmonary artery and vein. The finding could be explained by non-involvement
of typical IP receptors.
Most PGI2 agonist drugs cause nonspecific gastric side-effects like abdominal
cramps, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea in patients receiving them. Previous
binding assays demonstrated that both beraprost and iloprost have a high
affinity for prostaglandin receptors-1& 3 (EP1 and EP3), and these receptor
subtypes have been found to mediate contraction of rat gastric fundus. Since
selexipag and its active ingredient (ACT-333679) have demonstrated specific
binding to IP receptors in pulmonary arteries, they are expected to cause
minimal gastrointestinal adverse effects posed by other PGI2 agonists. Using rat
gastric fundus in a preclinical animal study, it was shown that ex-vivo selexipag
and its metabolite (ACT-333679) failed to contract gastric fundus at
concentrations up to 10-3 M, which is the therapeutic level of selexipag. In stark
contrast, the other PGI2 analogs iloprost and beraprost evoked concentration-
dependent contraction of gastric fundus which was shown to be mediated
mostly by EP3 receptors, although EP1 receptors were also involved in both
cases. In vivo, they showed oral selexipag did not slow down the rates of gastric
emptying and intestinal transport. [45] However, beraprost was shown to slow
gastrointestinal transport in vivo in the same study, which clearly drives home
the point that oral selexipag may actually help minimize gastric side effects
such as nausea and vomiting which are the primary causes of discomfort for the
patients taking a PGI2 agonist.
Clinical data on Selexipag
Phase I
In the first of its kind, a double-blind, randomized, placebo-controlled, dose
escalation Phase I clinical trial was conducted over 64 non-smoker healthy
males, to assess the pharmacokinetics (PK) of single ascending doses (SAD)
and multiple ascending doses (MAD). The effect of food on PK of selexipag
and its active metabolite ACT-333679, along with their tolerability were also
evaluated in this trial. Two-period crossover model was applied for this
secondary objective. The results of this trial validated the fact that while a single
dose of selexipag was well tolerated at the 100, 200, and 400 mg, but single
doses of 600 and 800 mg caused increased severity and incidence of adverse
effects (AEs) such as a headache, nausea, dizziness, and vomiting. The
tolerance of this drug is increased with incremental up-titration, which became
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
evident from MAD part of this study, where a dosing regimen of 600 mg
selexipag twice daily was well tolerated following up-titration from 400 mg.
The mean half-lives of selexipag and ACT-333679 were calculated to be 0.7
2.3 hrs and 9.414.22 hrs respectively. It also concluded that selexipag is
mainly eliminated via the hepatobiliary route as the low concentration of ACT-
333679 was measured in urine. There was no significant effect of food on the
extent of exposure to selexipag, but its active metabolite ACT-33679 had a
decreased exposure of 27% in the presence of food. [22]
In another Phase I double-blind, placebo-controlled, randomized, multiple
ascending dose, up-titration study, the safety, tolerability, pharmacokinetics,
and pharmacodynamics of selexipag were duly assessed in 16 healthy male
healthy subjects. Oral administration of incremental doses of selexipag, up to a
level of 1600 mg, was found to be well tolerated in this study. The dose of 1600
mg was identified as the maximum tolerated dose of this drug. This study was
unique as it conferred that although the plasma exposure to ACT-333679 was
approximately four times higher than that to selexipag, yet the pharmacokinetics
of selexipag and ACT-333679 were dose proportional. [47]
The third phase 1 study, which included 80 healthy male subjects,
bioequivalence of the dose of selexipag was demonstrated between 8 x 200 g
and 1 x 1,600 g selexipag at steady state, and the adverse effects were not
found to be different between the two doses in the two treatment groups.[46]
Although the adverse effects were not significant between two treatment groups,
the headache was the most frequent adverse effect while myalgia and jaw pain
were second and third most common respectively.
Keeping in mind the fact that warfarin is routinely prescribed as a mode of
anticoagulation to patients with PAH, a recently published phase I study looked
at the potential pharmacodynamic and pharmacokinetic interactions between
selexipag and warfarin. [50] In this double-blind, 2-way, 2-treatment crossover
study, 19 healthy men were recruited. They were administered a single dose of
selexipag 400 g or placebo on day 1, followed by twice daily doses of
selexipag or placebo on days 2-12. Additionally, a single dose of warfarin 20
mg was administered to all on day 8. Overall the drug regimen was well
tolerated in this study, except for few minor adverse effects like a headache. The
geometric mean ratio of INR (with 90% CI) during treatment with selexipag and
warfarin versus warfarin alone, were within the reference limit (0.80-1.25). The
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
steady state AUC of selexipag and its active metabolite (ACT-333679) was
unaffected by the single dose of warfarin. Similarly, oral selexipag or ACT-
333679 did not have any demonstrable influence on warfarin
pharmacodynamics. Overall, this study failed to show any significant drug
interactions between selexipag and warfarin.
Phase II
In a phase-II study, 43 adult patients with PAH, who were symptomatic despite
receiving an endothelin receptor antagonist and a phosphodiesterase type-5
inhibitor, were administered either selexipag or placebo. [51] For a patient to be
enrolled, he or she needed to have a baseline PVR of 400 dyn.s.cm-5. Subjects
also required to have two 6-min walk tests of 150500 m inclusive and within
15% of each other. Patients with a history of clinically unstable right heart
failure in last three months were excluded from the study. The primary end-
point of the study was the change in PVR at week 17. The study confirmed a
significant 30.3% reduction in PVR after 17 weeks treatment with selexipag
compared to placebo. The secondary endpoints of the study included 6-min
walk distance, worsening of PAH (death, transplantation, hospitalization due to
PAH, or aggravation of symptoms as measured by 6-min walk distance or the
need for additional PAH-specific therapies). Other measured secondary
endpoints were Borg dyspnoea score, WHO-Functional Class, and plasma NT-
pro-BNP levels. [52-54] Selexipag was found to increase 6-min walk distance
(396.271.4 vs. 350.3123.5 in placebo) and also decrease in Borg dyspnoea
score (3.32.1 in selexipag vs. 4.12.6 in placebo) and plasma NT-pro-BNP
level (1601.42443.0 in selexipag group vs. 2400.91269.8 in placebo). This
beneficial effect of selexipag was seen without significant hypotension despite
the considerable decrease in systemic vascular resistance (SVR). The 17 weeks
treatment with selexipag was well tolerated by most patients in this study, and
the adverse effect profile was very similar to what has been shown before. This
study confirms the beneficial effect of selexipag as an add-on therapy to the
already existing treatment regimen in patients with PAH.
Prospective open-label studies looked at the possible alterations in the
pharmacokinetics of selexipag and its active metabolite in patients with hepatic
or, renal impairment. After administration of a single dose of 200 g or 400 g
of selexipag, the area under the concentration-time curve from time zero to
infinity (AUC 0-) was determined to assess the pharmacokinetic profile of the
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
drug and its active metabolite (ACT-333679). It was noted that there is a
significant increase in exposure (expressed as AUC 0-) with advancing
severity of hepatic impairment. A 4.5-fold increase in AUC for selexipag and
2.2-fold for ACT-333679 were noted in patients with moderate hepatic
impairment when compared with healthy subjects. The exposure was also more
in subjects with a severe degree of renal function impairment. Despite this
observed heightened exposure, there were no safety concerns raised in all these
groups of patients. This study showed that no adjustment in the starting dose of
selexipag is required for patients with mild hepatic impairment or severe renal
function impairment, though one should be very cautious during dosage up-
titration in moderate to severe hepatic impairment. [55]
Phase III
Prostacyclin (PGI2) receptor agonist in pulmonary arterial hypertension
(GRIPHON) study is the only event-driven, phase 3, randomized, double-blind,
placebo-controlled clinical trial on selexipag. In this study, near about 1156
patients with PAH were included to administer selexipag in individualized
doses (maximum dose, 1600 g twice daily) or placebo. [56] Eligibility of
inclusion in this study was determined by their past treatment history of PAH or
if they were treated with an endothelin receptor antagonist or a
phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitor, or both. Patients were enrolled in such a way
that they had a pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) of at the minimum 5 Wood
units (400 dyn.sec.cm-5) and a 6-minute walk distance of 50 to 450 m.
Selexipag was started at a dose of 200 g twice daily and was gradually up-
titrated in the increment of 200 g weekly until the development of a headache
or jaw pain which are common adverse effects of prostacyclins. Then the dose
was reduced by 200 g in both daily doses. The maximum dose permitted was
1600 g twice daily. The maintenance phase started after 12 weeks, but if
needed the dose could be decreased at any point in time. In this cohort, 133
patients (23.2%) got the low-dose stratum maintenance dose, 179 (31.2%)
patients received a medium stratum dose, whereas another 246 (42.9%) received
high-dose stratum maintenance dose. The primary end point in GRIPHON was
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
considered as death from any cause including complication related to PAH at
the end of the treatment period which was defined as seven days after the date
of the last intake of selexipag or placebo. The measured secondary endpoints
included the change in the 6-minute walk distance from the baseline, death, or
hospitalization due to uncontrolled PAH, or mortality due to any other cause
during the study period.
The primary endpoint event was seen in 397 patients 41.6% in the placebo
group and 27.0% in the selexipag group (HR 0.60; 99% CI, 0.46 - 0.78;
P<0.001). Approximately 102 patients (17.8%) in the selexipag group died due
to PAH or hospitalization from worsening of PAH symptoms, compared to 137
patients (23.5%) in the placebo group (hazard ratio 0.70; 95% CI, 0.54 to 0.91;
P=0.003) after completion of treatment period. It was also found that 87.4% of
these events were hospitalizations. The effect of selexipag on the primary
outcome was consistent across the strata irrespective of getting variable doses of
selexipag. It was noted that the 6-minute walk distance had increased by 4.0 m
from baseline at 26th week in the selexipag group in comparison to placebo
group where it was decreased by a median of 9.0 m from baseline (treatment
effect, 12.0 m; 99% CI, 1 to 24; P = 0.003). No statistically significant
difference was noted between the two groups, with respect to the proportion of
patients having no deterioration in WHO functional class (74.9% and 77.8%,
respectively; OR 1.16; 99% CI- 0.81 to 1.66; P = 0.28). Premature
discontinuation of the assigned regimen due to adverse effects (nausea, diarrhea,
headache, and jaw pain) was observed in 14.3% of patients in the selexipag
group, as opposed to 7.1% of patients on placebo. It was also seen in GRIPHON
study that the adverse events with selexipag occurred more commonly during
the dose-adjustment phase. By the time study was concluded, 105 patients in the
placebo group and 100 patients in the selexipag group had already died (due to
any cause), which shows that selexipag probably does not improve the overall
morbidity in PAH patients. Most common adverse events found in the selexipag
group were in the lines of previously shown side-effects of prostacyclin
inhibitors.
This clinical trial proves that the lower risk of the primary outcome in patients
with PAH was statistically significant in comparison with placebo, but there
was no major difference in all-cause mortality between the two treatment
groups. GRIPHON also demonstrated that the effect of selexipag was consistent
in all pre-specified patient subgroups that were defined according to the causes
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
of PAH, disease severity, and baseline treatment. The addition of selexipag to
the baseline treatment with two medications for PAH is beneficial. These data
strongly speak for the dose titration of selexipag to the highest possible dose
which the patient can tolerate with minimal side effects. But there was no
significant difference in all-cause mortality between the selexipag and placebo
groups in the GRIPHON study. One explanation of this can be the study design
itself, in which a sizeable proportion of patients who had a primary outcome,
crossed over to open-label selexipag or a commercially available drug, thus
making the quantification of death events very difficult. GRIPHON study had
its share of limitations. Due to the inclusion of an optional post-treatment
observation period after medication discontinuation, follow-up data on patients
who stopped the drugs was limited. Secondly, 18.9% of patients discontinued
placebo or selexipag prematurely which was anticipated earlier and the attrition
bias was accounted for in this study. A final limitation lay in fixation of the
primary end points based on recommendations of pivotal randomized,
controlled trials in PAH patients, and the inclusion of some subjective
components in those. [57] Due to these limitations of this study owing to drug
discontinuation and the subjective nature of the primary endpoints, future large-
scale clinical trials studies may help ameliorate these issues.
Another major potential side effect of every drug is drug-induced QT interval
prolongation which invariably increases the risk of torsades de pointes and
resultant sudden cardiac death. As per International Conference on
Harmonisation E14 guidance, the effects of selexipag and its active metabolite
ACT-333679 on cardiac repolarization were evaluated compared to a positive
control (moxifloxacin) in QT study.[44] They used the 800 mg and 1600 mg
drug dose as they are being employed in the GRIPHON Study and found that
the exposure-response analysis did not show a pertinent relationship between
plasma concentrations of Selexipag or ACT-333679 and QTc and concluded
that Selexipag did not have any significant effect on cardiac repolarization.
It has also been previously shown that the metabolism of selexipag involves
CYP2C8 and CYP3A4 and UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT) enzymes,
UGT1A3 and UGT2B7 are participating in the metabolism (Actelion
Pharmaceuticals Ltd,). In vitro, both selexipag and ACT-333679 have been
found to be weak substrates of OATP1B1 and OATP1B3, while selexipag alone
is a weak substrate of the efflux pump P-gp. Since lopinavir and ritonavir are
known inhibitors of OATP1B1, OATP1B3, CYP3A4 and P-gp, an open-label,
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
randomized, single center, two-way, crossover study was performed to evaluate
the possible effect of the fixed dose combination of lopinavir/ritonavir on the
PK of selexipag or its metabolite. [58, 59] This could also evaluate the
tolerability of single dose selexipag when administered alone or in combination
with lopinavir/ritonavir in this fixed combination could serve as a model
inhibitor to gain a thorough insight into the drugdrug interaction propensity of
selexipag and its principal metabolite. The results of this study suggested that
when lopinavir/ ritonavir was given together with selexipag, the extent of
change in PK parameters of selexipag and its principal active metabolite ACT-
333679 is very similar to the PK parameters when Selexipag was given alone
and did not reach the level of any clinically meaningful interaction. Therefore, it
can well be concluded that change in the dosage of Selexipag may not be
required when it is administered in adjunct with inhibitors of transporters
OATP1B1/OATP1B3 (e.g. atazanavir, cyclosporin), P-gp (e.g. verapamil,
ketoconazole, tacrolimus) or CYP3A4 (e.g. saquinavir, ketoconazole,
clarithromycin).
Conclusion and future directions
Although not currently in use, selexipag is the latest PGI2 agonist which
appears as a promising treatment option for PAH. It is the sole drug directed
towards the prostacyclin pathway which is currently recommended for
incremental double and triple combination therapy in patients who have WHO
FC II and III (i.e. selexipag along with an ERA and/or, PDE-5i). Since it is a
specific agonist of IP receptor and does not act on other prostacyclin receptors,
it has a much milder side-effect profile which makes it a very lucrative
therapeutic option. Its longer half-life requiring twice daily dosage and oral
route of administration of Selexipag make patient compliance to it relatively
easier. Given the PAH disease pathology involving three distinct pathways in
the body, it is pretty imperative that the need to stop every disease pathway with
suitable drugs without additional and synergistic significant side-effects was
truly the need of the hour. Selexipag appears to provide physicians with such an
option where they can effectively treat the patients already on the combination
therapies of ET receptor antagonist and NO receptor agonist. The only
drawback that Selexipag may face is its ineffectiveness to lower all-cause
mortality in Phase 3 GRIPHON trial. Another question which will continue to
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
be raised is whether to start the Selexipag in the disease onset when PAH has
been recently diagnosed or to use it in late stage PAH when considerable
disease progression has already occurred. Since in GRIPHON study, Selexipag
was given to the patients who were not on the treatment for PAH or a stable
dose of an endothelin-receptor antagonist, a phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitor,
or a combination of both, it is extremely difficult to confer whether Selexipag
can be used alone or in combination of PDE-5i PDE inhibitors and ET receptor
blockers to gain this beneficial effect in PAH patients.
The ongoing Phase 3 study TRITON (Triple Versus Initial Dual Oral
Combination Therapy in Patients With Newly Diagnosed Pulmonary Arterial
Hypertension) is trying to compare the efficacy and safety of an initial triple
oral treatment regimen (macitentan, tadalafil, and selexipag) with an initial dual
oral treatment regimen (macitentan, tadalafil, placebo) in newly diagnosed,
untreated PAH patients. Since their primary outcome depends on PVR after 26
weeks of starting the treatment, it can be an excellent indicator of the beneficial
effects of Selexipag alone in PAH patients in reducing its morbidity and
mortality. As other prostacyclin inhibitors have documented beneficial effects in
PAH patients but their limitation lies in their short half-life, another ongoing
phase 3 Study TRANSIT-1 (Tolerability and the Safety of the Transition from
Inhaled Treprostinil to Oral Selexipag in Patients with Pulmonary Arterial
Hypertension) fits well into the picture. Safety and tolerability of oral selexipag
will be evaluated in TRANSIT-1 among patients who changed therapy from
inhaled treprostinil. Also it will evaluate the effects of oral Selexipag on PAH
severity and exercise ability before and after transition and also gain new
information about the patients experience of taking oral selexipag, as compared
to inhaled treprostinil. Their primary outcome is sustained treatment transition
till week 16, treatment-emergent adverse events (AEs), treatment-emergent
serious adverse events (SAEs), AEs leading to premature discontinuation of
study treatment, vital signs during treatment, Selexipag dose and finally time to
discontinuation of inhaled treprostinil. Their secondary outcome included
clinical estimation/ quantification parameters of PAH-like WHO functional
class (FC), change in 6-minute walk distance (6MWD), the proportion of
patients with a change in 6MWD N-terminal pro b-type natriuretic peptide (NT-
proBNP). Other additional parameters that are being studied in TRANSIT-1 are
treatment satisfaction "effectiveness," treatment satisfaction "side effects,"
treatment satisfaction "convenience" and finally treatment satisfaction "global
satisfaction." So TRITON and TRANSIT-1 studies can be expected to direct the
This article is protected by copyright. All rights reserved.
plan of action regarding Selexipag use in PAH patients. All the current and
completed trials on selexipag have been summarized in Table 3.
Thus it can be concluded that although the ideal time point of starting PAH
patients on selexipag for maximum benefit remains unclear, it will not be wrong
to state that selexipag, with the proof of its effectiveness in significantly
decreasing the death and hospitalization in PAH patients with minimum side
effect profile, can turn out to be the game-changer in modern day treatment
guidelines of PAH. With the results of the ongoing phase 3 studies (TRITON
and TRANSIT-1) being available, we will have a better idea about the safety
and efficacy of oral selexipag as a part of the initial regimen in newly diagnosed
PAH patients, as well as in those who are in transition from another mode of
therapy.

Table 1: Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension (PAH) Key Highlights
PAH also known as Group 1 PH as per WHO classification.
Idiopathic PAH is the commonest type.
Three major pathways involved in PAH pathogenesis including ET-1, NO, and
Prostacyclin (PGI2).
Decreased expression of Prostacyclin synthase and reduced level of endogenous
PGI2 seen in PAH.
[Abbreviations: PAH-Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension, PH- Pulmonary Hypertension, ET-
Endothelin, NO-Nitric Oxide, PGI2 - Prostacyclin]
TABLE 2: Highlights of Selexipag Pharmacology
A selective Prostacyclin (IP) receptor agonist.
Oral route of administration with rapid absorption.
Active metabolite ACT-333679 formed in liver.
ACT-333679 has a 13-fold higher affinity for IP receptors.
Elimination of Selexipag and ACT-333679 primarily through hepatobiliary
route.
Maximum tolerated daily dose of Selexipag is 1600 g.
Minimal gastric adverse effects noted.
